">10.1002/alz.13915</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType=\"pmc\">PMC11350008</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType=\"pubmed\">38923692</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Natera-de Benito D, Olival J, Garcia-Cabau C, Jou C, Roldan M, Codina A, Exp&#xf3;sito-Escudero J, Batlle C, Carrera-Garc&#xed;a L, Ortez C, Salvatella X, Palau F, Nascimento A, Hoenicka J (2023) Common pathophysiology for ANXA11 disorders caused by aspartate 40 variants. Ann Clin Transl Neurol 10(3):408&#x2013;425. 10.1002/acn3.51731</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType=\"doi\">10.1002/acn3.51731</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType=\"pmc\">PMC10014011</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType=\"pubmed\">36651622</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Leoni TB, Gonz&#xe1;lez-Salazar C, Rezende TJR, Hern&#xe1;ndez ALC, Mattos AHB, Coimbra Neto AR, da Gra&#xe7;a FF, Gon&#xe7;alves JPN, Martinez ARM, Taniguti L, Kitajima JP, Kok F, Rog&#xe9;rio F, da Silva AMS, de Oliveira ALR, Zanoteli E, Nucci A, Fran&#xe7;a MC Jr (2021) A novel multisystem proteinopathy caused by a missense ANXA11 variant. Ann Neurol 90(2):239&#x2013;252. 10.1002/ana.26136</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType=\"doi\">10.1002/ana.26136</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType=\"pubmed\">34048612</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Kim EJ, Moon SY, Kim HJ, Jung NY, Lee SM, Kim YE (2022) Semantic variant primary progressive aphasia with a pathogenic variant p.Asp40Gly in the ANXA11 gene. Eur J Neurol 29(10):3124&#x2013;3126. 10.1111/ene.15455</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType=\"doi\">10.1111/ene.15455</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType=\"pubmed\">36073198</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Zhang X, Gao J, Chi C, Zhao Z, Chan P, Ma J (2023) An atypical ALS with PSP-like symptoms caused by <i>ANXA11</i> p. D40G mutation: a case report and literature review. Front Neurol 14:1086264. 10.3389/fneur.2023.1086264\n</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType=\"doi\">10.3389/fneur.2023.1086264</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType=\"pmc\">PMC9978770</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType=\"pubmed\">36873447</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference><Reference><Citation>Goutman SA, Hardiman O, Al-Chalabi A, Chi&#xf3; A, Savelieff MG, Kiernan MC, Feldman EL (2022) Recent advances in the diagnosis and prognosis of amyotrophic lateral sclerosis. Lancet Neurol 21(5):480&#x2013;493. 10.1016/S1474-4422(21)00465-8</Citation><ArticleIdList><ArticleId IdType=\"doi\">10.1016/S1474-4422(21)00465-8</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType=\"pmc\">PMC9513753</ArticleId><ArticleId IdType=\"pubmed\">35334233</ArticleId></ArticleIdList></Reference></ReferenceList></PubmedData></PubmedArticle><PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status=\"MEDLINE\" Owner=\"NLM\" IndexingMethod=\"Automated\"><PMID Version=\"1\">40707625</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2025</Year><Month>09</Month><Day>02</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>01</Month><Day>27</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel=\"Print-Electronic\"><Journal><ISSN IssnType=\"Electronic\">1460-2075</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium=\"Internet\"><Volume>44</Volume><Issue>17</Issue><PubDate><Year>2025</Year><Month>Sep</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>The EMBO journal</Title><ISOAbbreviation>EMBO J</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>ALS-associated RNA-binding proteins promote UNC13A transcription through REST downregulation.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>4745</StartPage><EndPage>4771</EndPage><MedlinePgn>4745-4771</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType=\"doi\" ValidYN=\"Y\">10.1038/s44318-025-00506-0</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS) is a neurodegenerative disease characterized by selective loss of motor neurons. Although multiple pathophysiological mechanisms have been identified, no comprehensive understanding of these heterogeneous processes has been achieved. The ALS-associated RNA-binding protein (RBP) TDP-43 has previously been shown to stabilize UNC13A mRNA by preventing cryptic exon inclusion. Here, we show that the ALS-associated RBPs MATR3, FUS, and hnRNPA1 regulate UNC13A expression by targeting the transcriptional repressor REST. These RBPs bind to and downregulate REST mRNA to promote UNC13A transcription. Loss of any of these RBPs in cultured cells or in iPSC-derived motor neurons carrying the ALS-causing FUS P525L mutation leads to REST overexpression, and the same is observed in motor neurons of individuals with familial or sporadic ALS. The functional convergence of four RBPs on the regulation of UNC13A expression underscores the important role of this process for synaptic integrity, and its association with ALS pathogenesis could be relevant for the development of new therapeutic agents.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>&#xa9; 2025. The Author(s).</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN=\"Y\"><Author ValidYN=\"Y\"><LastName>Watanabe</LastName><ForeName>Yasuaki</ForeName><Initials>Y</Initials><Identifier Source=\"ORCID\">0009-0006-3347-1628</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Neurology, Graduate School of Medicine, Tohoku University, Sendai, Miyagi, 980-8575, Japan. yasuaki.watanabe.b8@tohoku.ac.jp.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Division of Cell Proliferation, ART, Graduate School of Medicine, Tohoku University, Sendai, Miyagi, 980-8575, Japan. yasuaki.watanabe.b8@tohoku.ac.jp.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN=\"Y\"><LastName>Suzuki</LastName><ForeName>Naoki</ForeName><Initials>N</Initials><Identifier Source=\"ORCID\">0000-0001-8880-8554</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Neurology, Graduate School of Medicine, Tohoku University, Sendai, Miyagi, 980-8575, Japan.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Rehabilitation Medicine, Graduate School of Medicine, Tohoku University, Sendai, Miyagi, 980-8575, Japan.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN=\"Y\"><LastName>Nakagawa</LastName><ForeName>Tadashi</ForeName><Initials>T</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Division of Cell Proliferation, ART, Graduate School of Medicine, Tohoku University, Sendai, Miyagi, 980-8575, Japan.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Clinical Pharmacology, Faculty of Pharmaceutical Sciences, Sanyo-Onoda City University, Sanyo-Onoda, 756-0884, Japan.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN=\"Y\"><LastName>Hosogane</LastName><ForeName>Masaki</ForeName><Initials>M</Initials><Identifier Source=\"ORCID\">0000-0001-5784-304X</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Division of Cell Proliferation, ART, Graduate School of Medicine, Tohoku University, Sendai, Miyagi, 980-8575, Japan.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN=\"Y\"><LastName>Akiyama</LastName><ForeName>Tetsuya</ForeName><Initials>T</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Neurology, Graduate School of Medicine, Tohoku University, Sendai, Miyagi, 980-8575, Japan.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN=\"Y\"><LastName>Kageyama</LastName><ForeName>Naotoshi</ForeName><Initials>N</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Division of Cell Proliferation, ART, Graduate School of Medicine, Tohoku University, Sendai, Miyagi, 980-8575, Japan.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN=\"Y\"><LastName>Funayama</LastName><ForeName>Yukino</ForeName><Initials>Y</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Department of Neurology, Graduate School of Medicine, Tohoku University, Sendai, Miyagi, 980-8575, Japan.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>Division of Cell Proliferation, ART, Graduate School of Medicine, Tohoku University, Sendai, Miyagi, 980-8575, Japan.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN=\"Y\"><LastName>Warita</LastName><ForeName>Hitoshi</ForeName><Initials>H</Initials><Identifier Source=\"ORCID\">0000-0001-7934-3863</Identifier><AffiliationInfo><Affil